    {
      "id": "500e9270_37faf4ab",
      "file_path": "runtime-controlloop/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/clamp/controlloop/runtime/commissioning/rest/CommissioningController.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 23,
      "message": "oh, it isn't using jackson to translate data, it's using it to dump a schema.  Then probably ok to use it.  However, these classes do not typically have any jackson annotations, so may not yield correct output.  For example, a lot of these classes are subclasses of ToscaEntity, which contains a \"derivedFrom\" field, which is serialized as \"derived_from\".  Does that should up correctly in the output from the \"schema\" method below?  (And I don't want to introduce jackson into policy-models, if we can avoid it, because that may force us to deal with vulnerability issues reported on IQ.  Though just including the jackson annotations jar for models might be ok.)",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2021-07-09 16:14:41.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "80914689_b90fc311",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "e89d0560_8bc6dd5b",
      "file_path": "runtime-controlloop/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/clamp/controlloop/runtime/commissioning/rest/CommissioningController.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 409,
      "message": "Ack",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2021-07-09 16:14:41.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "b2993e06_97ed34df",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "c9d3c08c_b6896fe0",
      "file_path": "runtime-controlloop/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/clamp/controlloop/runtime/commissioning/rest/CommissioningController.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 23,
      "message": "That will be ok I think. I am converting the camel case in the output Json Schema to snake case in the endpoint function. So derivedFrom gets changed to derived_from\n\nObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();\nmapper.setPropertyNamingStrategy(PropertyNamingStrategies.SNAKE_CASE);\n\nThat gets me what I want. Won't need to change the models I don't think.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 7603,
        "name": "Saul Gill",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "saul.gill@est.tech",
        "username": "saul.gill"
      },
      "updated": "2021-07-09 16:22:27.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "500e9270_37faf4ab",
      "unresolved": true
    },
